Regression: Full suite of 153 tests across all 4 internal packages:
  internal/llm:   12 tests — all PASS
  internal/loop:  43 tests — all PASS (30 original + 13 new)
  internal/store:  16 tests — all PASS
  internal/tools:  82 tests — all PASS
  go build ./... — clean
  go vet ./... — clean

Findings / notes:

1. Delta check adds unaccounted LLM calls. The delta check calls
   l.llm.Call (or DeltaCheckLLM if set), which increment the Fake's
   CallCount. This means LLM-call-count assertions in tests must account
   for 1 extra call every 5 turns. The existing builder tests didn't
   account for this because they only test assertorical halt codes, not
   exact call counts. The tester's new tests explicitly account for it.

2. Session ID is not exposed. Run() returns HaltReason (Code, Message,
   ResumeCount) but does NOT expose the session ID. This prevents tests
   from querying session status ("error" vs "halted") or event counts
   from the store. For Phase 4, consider adding a session ID accessor or
   including it in HaltReason.

3. Content-hash vs write-count interaction with file-already-edited. The
   write-count halt detection test (TestHardcoded_WriteCountThreshold)
   uses the same edit_file(old_str="a",new_str="b") on every turn. After
   the first edit, the file content changes to "b", so subsequent edits
   fail with ErrNoMatch. The loop counts these as write attempts via
   UpsertFile's ON CONFLICT increment, but the tool returns an error
   each time. This means the write-count test works via ERROR writes,
   not SUCCESS writes — which is fine behaviorally but worth documenting.

4. No contradictions found between ADR and .feature files. All behaviors
   tested match both the ADR's design and the .feature's expectations.
   No agent output needs revisiting.

Phase 3 is ready to merge per §15.

=== Architect entry — Fix Cycle 2 (2026-07-06) ===

Deliverable: docs/adr-phase-3-turn-loop.md §14 (appended)

Issue: The Option B design (§10) correctly identified that the caller must
resolve the project root once via EvalSymlinks and pass the same resolved
value to both tools.NewDefaultRegistry and loop.New. However, the design
relied on the caller remembering this convention — nothing structurally
prevented a mismatch. In TestTester_SymlinkEndToEndThroughLoop, the raw
unresolved symDir was passed to both calls; NewDefaultRegistry resolved it
internally but loop.New stored the raw value verbatim, creating a divergence
between ToolConfig.ProjectRoot and the tools' internal root.

Fix: Changed NewDefaultRegistry's signature to return (Registry, string)
instead of Registry alone. The second return value is the EvalSymlinks-
resolved root. Callers that construct a TurnLoop MUST source resolvedRoot
from this return value and pass it to loop.New (whose signature is unchanged).
This makes the mismatch structurally impossible because the resolved root is
computed in exactly one place and flows to both consumers from there.

Changes required (35 call sites):

  - internal/tools/tools.go: NewDefaultRegistry returns (Registry, string).
  - internal/tools/tools_test.go: 5 sites — add _ discard for 2nd value.
  - internal/loop/loop_test.go: 2 sites — capture resolvedRoot, pass to New().
    Also fix ToolConfig.ProjectRoot in TestSymlink_AllowPathWithSymlinkedRoot
    to use resolvedRoot instead of symDir.
  - internal/loop/tester_phase3_test.go: 1 site — unchain .FilterByAgentConfig()
    to capture resolvedRoot.
  - e2e/phase2_test.go: 27 sites — add _ discard for 2nd value.

loop.New signature unchanged. No new Option-A-vs-B ambiguity: this is a
structural hardening of Option B, not a revert to the type-assertion approach.

Verification: go build ./..., go vet ./..., go test ./... all pass after
updates. TestTester_SymlinkEndToEndThroughLoop now exercises the full
path with matching roots.

